==Latin==

===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|ine-pro|la}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*deyḱ-||to show, point out}}. Cognates include Oscan {{term|𐌃𐌄𐌉𐌊𐌖𐌌||to show, point out|tr=deíkum|lang=osc}}, Sanskrit {{term|sc=Deva|दिशति|tr=diśáti|lang=sa}}, Ancient Greek {{term|sc=polytonic|δείκνυμι|tr=deiknumi|lang=grc}} and Old English {{term/t|ang|tǣċan}} (English {{term|teach|lang=ang}}).

====Pronunciation====
* {{IPA|lang=la|/ˈdiː.koː/|lang=la}}
* {{audio|la-cls-dico-long.ogg|Audio (Classical)}}

====Verb====
{{la-verb|dico|dīcō|dicere|dīcere|dixi|dīxī|dictum|dictum}}

# I [[say]], [[utter]]; [[mention]]; [[talk]], [[speak]].
#: '''''Dixit''' duas res ei rubori fuisse.''
#:: He '''said''' that two things had abashed him.
# I [[declare]], [[state]].
## I [[affirm]], [[assert]] (positively).
# I [[tell]].
#* '''c. 254–184 {{B.C.E.}}''', [[w:Plautus|Plautus]], [[w:Captivi|Captivi]] ("The Captives"), 623, ([http://www.ihaystack.com/authors/m/plautus_titus_maccius/00016564_amphitryo_asinaria_aulularia_bacchides_captivi_amphi/00016564_englishlatin_utf8_p043.htm English and Latin text])
#*: Eho '''dic''' mihi, quis illic igitur est?
#*:: Hey? '''Tell''' me, who is he then?
# I [[appoint]], [[fix]], [[name]] (to an office).
# I [[call]], name.
# {{context|legal|followed by ad|lang=la}} I [[plead]] (before).
# I speak in [[reference]] to, [[refer]] to.

=====Inflection=====
* The singular imperative, {{term|dice|dīce}}, was later shortened to {{term||dīc}}.
{{la-conj-3rd-dico|dīc|dīx|dict|11=dic|22=dix|33=dict}}

